{
  "texts": [
    "These were formulated with input from multiple stakeholders at various institutions, and are summarized in Table 1: Google Flu TrendsThe Google Flu Trends (GFT) system was designed and first launched in 2008 to help predict outbreaks of flu.",
    "After initial success, it became plagued with significant errors and it was discontinued from producing new predictions on 9 August 2015.",
    "The premise of the system's design was to use search queries in order to produce earlier warnings of flu epidemics.",
    "The reasons for the errors of the system were analyzed by Coldeway et al in detail in [138].",
    "The main factors identified by these researchers (which are directly addressed by best practices in the present volume) were:(a) Bad data design (\"Big Data hubris\") in which the designers relied on large volumes of biased data instead of eliminating systematic biases (such as that searches about Flu symptoms are also linked with other diseases leading thus to overestimating the incidence of flu)."
  ]
}